      "rationale": "Nonlinear quasi-static solver converged to residual norm below 1e-7 for all 25 load increments in each simulation. Energy balance error remained below 0.05% throughout. No spurious contact oscillations detected in force-displacement curves."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup by second analyst; documented simulation plan reviewed prior to execution.",
      "rationale": "A documented simulation plan specifying boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, and load application was reviewed and approved by a second analyst before execution. Post-processing scripts were independently verified against hand calculations for three representative load steps."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elastic-plastic constitutive model with frictional contact at screw-rod and screw-vertebra interfaces; model form justified by literature and prior FDA validation studies.",
      "rationale": "The pedicle screw construct is modeled as an elastic-plastic continuum using Ti-6Al-4V material properties from published literature. Frictional contact (μ=0.3) is applied at all metallic interfaces. This model form has been validated in prior FDA studies on similar spinal implant geometries and is appropriate for the quasi-static compression-bending regime."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from ASTM-certified coupon tests on same lot material; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of test specimens; uncertainty in inputs quantified and propagated.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa) measured from tensile coupons from the same material lot as test constructs. Screw and rod geometry digitized via CMM to ±0.01 mm. Monte Carlo propagation of input uncertainties contributed <3% to total model output uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs tested; specimens from production lot; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to design drawing.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from production-representative components were tested. Dimensional inspection of all specimens confirmed conformance to design drawing within specified tolerances. Two independent laboratories contributed data, providing inter-laboratory reproducibility evidence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of COU loading scenarios; at minimum two independent load magnitudes or configurations tested.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration (35 mm offset, 10 mm/min crosshead speed). Only one test condition was evaluated, falling short of the Gradation 3 requirement for multiple conditions. This factor is acknowledged as below required level; compensating evidence from the multi-laboratory design and large sample size partially offsets this gap."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model boundary conditions and material inputs match experimental conditions to within documented uncertainty; any discrepancies explicitly quantified.",
      "rationale": "Boundary conditions in the FEA (fixed base plate, roller at load application point, 35 mm moment arm) directly replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry. Material properties assigned from the same lot as test specimens. Discrepancies between nominal and measured specimen geometry were quantified and incorporated as input uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference <10% for all three QoIs across all three FEA environments.",
      "rationale": "For all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) across all three FEA environments, the validation metric E/uval ranged from 0.31 to 1.44, and percent differences ranged from 1.2% to 8.7%. All comparisons satisfied the pre-established acceptance criteria of E/uval < 1.96 and <10% difference."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) directly correspond to the decision-relevant mechanical performance attributes of the pedicle screw construct.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing with adjacent spinal levels; yield force indicates onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield behavior relevant to fatigue life prediction. All three QoIs are directly linked to the regulatory decision attributes for pedicle screw mechanical performance evaluation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments replicate COU geometry, material, loading mode, and boundary conditions; any differences between validation and COU contexts are explicitly documented and bounded.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the identical screw geometry, material, and ASTM F1717 test configuration as the COU. The only acknowledged difference is that the COU encompasses in vivo loading conditions beyond the single bench test configuration; this gap is bounded by the conservative nature of ASTM F1717 loading relative to physiological loads documented in the literature."
    }
